node.text:
It was August of last year when I decided to organize a whale watching trip for a dozen guests or so to go to Maui with me for the coming Humpback Whale season. With the state of the world and pandemic being what it was, I had really no idea if this trip was even going to be possible. Despite numerous roadblocks and setbacks, the @gonewhalewatching crew and 12 guests arrived in Maui a couple weeks ago and the trip was a monumental success. We kayaked with whales, dove in crystal clear blue water, and spent our days and evenings surrounded by hundreds of Humpback Whales. The highlight was one of our sunset whale watches with @ultimate_whalewatch_n_snorkel where we were mugged by FOUR Humpback Whales for over an hour. For just about everyone on board besides myself, Jen, and Taylor, this was their first time having any kind of encounter like this with a whale. I didn’t do much filming during that encounter, but I did stick my head in the water and look two curious Humpback Whales straight in the eye as they sang right next to me. It’s a moment that will stay with me the rest of my life.

Thank you to my GWW crew and all of my contributors to this video including @bluelifewild @hendo_k_ @_justalison_ @taylor.parent and @jbunz 

Can’t wait to announce more of these destination whale watching experiences for when the pandemic ends! 

#GoneWhaleWatchingInMaui

On Christmas Day I’ll be dropping a full length documentary based on my experiences in 2020. This footage was captured over the course of the past year by myself and my amazing crew members, and as you’ll see here, is also narrated by me. This is definitely outside of my comfort zone, but I have some major announcements on the horizon for 2021 where you’ll be seeing both myself and my content in a whole new way (I can’t say more at this time, but it’s major!). 
I hope you enjoy this short segment and I would love to hear your feedback in the comments!

Happy #WorldOceansDay everybody! Who can name all 13 species of cetacean in this video!? There’s one super tricky one!

This is the trailer to my 30 minute “Virtual Whale Watching Documentary” on YouTube. I’ve put the link in my bio for those of you that would like to see it. The full length video is 30 minutes long and one of the most comprehensive compilations of drone footage of cetaceans you’ll find anywhere! With things opening back up, I hope some of you make it out to San Diego this summer so I can show you these amazing animals in person with @gonewhalewatching!

WE ARE GOING BACK TO MAUI IN 2022 AND THE DATES ARE UP!

During the months of January through March,  Maui, Hawaii is home to one of the greatest whale watching spectacles on earth: A mass gathering of Humpback Whales in their winter breeding grounds!

I will be once again leading this five-day whale watching extravaganza February 8th-12th 2022! Included in your package is:

-Over 20 hours on the water with Maui's legendary Humpback Whales on a special low-to-the-water RIB boat led by myself, the Gone Whale Watching Team, and the best local guides on Maui

-Professional Photography Advice from myself and the Gone Whale Watching Crew

-Snorkel Opportunities at the island of Lānaʻ away from the crowds and tourists! Listen to the whales singing underwater as you explore this unique underwater oasis! Snorkel Gear included! (we do not swim with the whales as it is illegal on the island)

-Special commemorative t-shirt

-Free ticket to @gonewhalewatching San Diego

-Professional 4K "mini-documentary" of your adventure produced by myself and the GWW team

-A delicious welcome-dinner at one of Lahaina's best restaurants

Price is $1350 per person 
(airfare and accommodations not included)

Must call to book. 858 500 2568

50% Deposit due to reserve your spot. Remaining Balance due Feb. 1st 2022. Deposit is refundable through August 31st. After September 1st there is NO refunds.

This trip sold out quickly last year, so don’t delay and book your whale watching bucket-list trip of a lifetime!

#GoneWhaleWatchingInMaui

UPDATE: We need answers-
I reported this giant, 50+ mile oil slick near San Clemente Island to the Coast Guard at approx 1120am local time on Saturday. The CG took the report and information over VHF channel 16 and thanked me for the report. At the same time there was a smaller slick, one covering approximately 3 miles near the San Diego coastline that was also reported. This area is much more densely traveled than the remote waters I was in offshore, and thus impossible to ignore based on the sheer numbers of boaters that witnessed it. However, it seems our @gonewhalewatching boat was the ONLY boat to report seeing the larger slick offshore, and that makes sense as we were quite literally the only boat out there. What’s frustrating is as of noon yesterday, the coast guard claimed to have zero knowledge of the larger spill area offshore, and they were only addressing the smaller area near San Diego calling it a 100 gallon diesel spill with unknown origins.

Thanks to you all for sharing these videos on here and Facebook, we were able to gain enough attention that the coast guard contacted me yesterday to “learn about this larger spill for the first time”. You can imagine how frustrating that was for me, as I know of NUMEROUS people that had been relentlessly contacting the CG about this since Saturday, beyond my own personal publicly available report to the CG in real-time on Saturday. (VHF is recorded and public record)
Due to the sheer volume of diesel fuel in the area where we were, spanning at a minimum of 50 miles, there’s only a handful of vessels large enough to carry that amount fuel: Cargo ships, and Navy ships. All fuel spills are supposed to be IMMEDIATELY reported to the Coast Guard, and as of midnight last night, nobody has come forward to take responsibility. A spill of this magnitude in one of the most critical feeding spots for endangered Blue Whales can NOT be allowed to be swept under the rug! 

Please share everyone, we are making progress and we must get answers!

node.text:
The most tragic thing I’ve ever filmed: a pod of dolphins swimming through a giant oil spill. The spill is spanning an area covering more than 50 miles, and it is lurking just off the coast of San Diego. On today’s extended trip we made our way to our reliable Blue Whale hotspot near San Clemente Island and we were shocked when the whales seemingly vanished. Just 24 hours earlier this zone was full of the feeding giants. It was then that we began making our way south, and soon made this shocking discovery. Tragic doesn’t begin to cover it. For more than 50 miles the ocean was covered in a thick sheen of oil, a devastating tragedy for the environment. We know very little at this time, and we are trying to make these images go viral in hopes of getting some answers as to how this happened. More shocking yet, 70+ miles away back in coastal San Diego, the local whale watching boats reported an area thick with oil encroaching on the local waters as well. I truly hope this isn’t as bad as it appears, but if this oil is already in an area that spans at a minimum of 70 miles, we could have a catastrophe of unimaginable scale on our hands. Please share this video, we need answers. 
We’ve reached out to NOAA, the Coast Guard, and the EPA. We hope to have an update soon.

node.text:
Wait for it to hear the exhale of the largest set of lungs in the world!
One of my favorite things about watching a Blue Whale is waiting for them to reappear from the depths after a long feeding dive. I stare down at the ocean in hopes that the sea will begin to glow a vibrant sapphire blue color, indicating that a Blue Whale is about to surface! We had many moments like this yesterday, where the classic “blue glow” of the largest animal on earth was the first thing we saw before it broke the surface for a much needed breath! Filmed aboard @gonewhalewatching

node.text:
The largest animal on earth sliding through a sleek ocean surface made of glass. Blue Whales have arrived in big numbers in the outer waters off San Diego. While still the very beginning of the season, we saw over 20 Blue Whales on our most recent extended trip, with double digit Blue Whales on our last three voyages to the outer waters! With calm sea conditions forecasted the rest of this week, we’ve added yet another extended trip this Saturday! Don’t miss your rare chance to go on an full day trip with me on a weekend! Blue Whales are virtually guaranteed! Visit the link in my bio to book your trip! 
The 2.5 hour trips are seeing whales too, with it switching between Blue, Fin, and Humpback Whales each day! As we get deeper into June, Blue Whales will become more and more common locally! After such a choppy spring, booking a trip when the sea conditions are this calm is well worth it, and space remains this weekend! What are you waiting for!?
